</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1300201249;}i:4;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:61:"Zune Players are Dead, Move Along There?s Nothing to See Here";s:4:"link";s:62:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/15/zune-players-dead-move/";s:8:"comments";s:71:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/15/zune-players-dead-move/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 15 Mar 2011 10:00:35 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:17:"Mike Halsey (MVP)";}s:8:"category";s:22:"Windows 7 Hardwarezune";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://www.windows7news.com/?p=10933";s:11:"description";s:345:"It&#8217;s been expected for some time and following the integration of Zune services into Windows Phone, Microsoft has finally pulled the plug on its Zune hardware media players. Despite this the company will continue to use the name for selling music and video on Windows Phone and on the Xbox 360. The Zune was first released five years [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5380:"<p><a href="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/zune-review-zune-logo_1.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-10934" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/zune-review-zune-logo_1-150x150.jpg" alt="zune review zune logo 1 150x150 Zune Players are Dead, Move Along Theres Nothing to See Here" width="150" height="150" title="Zune Players are Dead, Move Along Theres Nothing to See Here" /></a>It&#8217;s been expected for some time and following the integration of Zune services into Windows Phone, Microsoft has finally pulled the plug on its Zune hardware media players.</p>
<p>Despite this the company will continue to use the name for selling music and video on Windows Phone and on the Xbox 360.</p>
<p>The Zune was first released five years ago but only ever went on sale in the US and, eventually, Canada.  Despite some gorgeous hardware for the latest generation device it came too late and was not widely enough sold to challenge Apple&#8217;s iPod.  The eventual worldwide launch of Windows Phone, each and every one containing the Zune player software, was the final nail in its coffin.</p>
<p>In a statement a Microsoft spokesperson said &#8220;We have nothing to announce about another Zune device.  Our long-term strategy focuses on the strength of the entire Zune ecosystem across Microsoft platforms, and we remain committed to providing a great music and video experience with the Zune service.&#8221;</p>
<p>It will be interesting to see what happens now as this could turn out to be extremely good news for <a href="http://www.windows8news.com">Windows 8</a> users in that it greatly increases the chance that the already excellent Zune desktop software will finally replace the ageing and creaking Windows Media Player in the next version of Microsoft&#8217;s desktop OS.</p>
<p>This is something that many commentators, myself included said should have happened with Windows 7.  It also raises questions about the Zune branding.  With no actual hardware devices being manufactured or being on sale any more there&#8217;s no actual need for the brand.  It&#8217;s entirely possible that all apps, music and video will be sold through the Windows 8 app store and this will become a single store for desktop, tablet and phone devices.  With the further possible integration of the Zune desktop software into Windows and the strong branding of Windows Phone there&#8217;s really no need to keep the Zune name around at all.</p>
<p>We&#8217;ll watch what Microsoft do carefully on this as report back as and when Microsoft decide to kill the Zune branding forever.</p>


