<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:D7DqB2pKExk"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:D7DqB2pKExk" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:I9og5sOYxJI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=I9og5sOYxJI" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=JaDqROJ0wJM:d1S11poKimw:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a>
</div>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:89:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/14/windows-phone-7-nodo-update-slightly-delayed/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"11";}s:7:"summary";s:345:"Microsoft&#8217;s Eric Hautala wrote in a blog post recently that the Windows Phone 7 &#8220;NoDo&#8221; update, which delivers copy and paste and other small improvements, would be released in late March instead of early March as previously indicated. This should come as little surprise to most of you, who can look at your calendars and [...]";s:12:"atom_content";s:5223:"<p>Microsoft&#8217;s Eric Hautala <a href="http://windowsteamblog.com/windows_phone/b/windowsphone/archive/2011/03/10/phone-updates-process-and-timing.aspx">wrote in a blog post recently</a> that the Windows Phone 7 &#8220;NoDo&#8221; update, which delivers copy and paste and other small improvements, would be released in late March instead of early March as previously indicated. This should come as little surprise to most of you, who can look at your calendars and see that anything resembling early March is just about to pass us by.</p>
<p>Hautala said that the update was being delayed at least in part because of problems some handset owners had with the last Windows Phone 7 update, which we <a href="http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/24/bad-news10-windows-phone-7-updates-fail/">wrote about</a> a few weeks back &#8211; while acknowledging that most users had been &#8220;successful&#8221; in installing the update, he said that Microsoft was &#8220;studying the current update process and will apply the lessons learned from it to all future ones.&#8221;</p>
<p>Of NoDo, he had this to say:</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;We have the next update waiting in the wings. It delivers copy and  paste, better Marketplace search, and other key improvements.</p>
<p>But  I believe it?s important that we learn all we can from the February  update. So I?ve decided to take some extra time to ensure the update  process meets our standards, your standards, and the standards of our  partners. As a result, our plan is to start delivering the  copy-and-paste update in the latter half of March.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>Hopefully this delay will ensure a smoother update process for all Windows Phone 7 users.</p>
<p>According to Hautala, the delay of the NoDo update shouldn&#8217;t at all affect the availability of future updates, which will bring Twitter integration and a new version of Internet Explorer Mobile, among other improvements.</p>
<p>The rest of the blog post goes into some detail about the Windows Phone 7 update mechanism itself, and offers a few interesting tidbits, including the extent to which all of the different carriers are responsible for providing new firmware to Microsoft, and for testing updates on their networks and handsets. It&#8217;s an interesting read, if you have a few minutes.</p>
<p>Source: <a href="http://windowsteamblog.com/windows_phone/b/windowsphone/archive/2011/03/10/phone-updates-process-and-timing.aspx">Windows Phone Blog</a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>


