</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1300143621;}i:6;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:45:"Deutsche Telekom Moves Computers to Windows 7";s:4:"link";s:78:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/14/deutch-telecom-moves-servers-windows-7/";s:8:"comments";s:87:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/14/deutch-telecom-moves-servers-windows-7/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 14 Mar 2011 21:49:03 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:6:"GGarza";}s:8:"category";s:28:"Windows 7 NewsDeutch Telecom";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://www.windows7news.com/?p=10929";s:11:"description";s:382:"Rack another one up for Microsoft Windows 7.  TSystems International a subsidiary of Deutsche Telekom AG announced that it is starting the migration operation of  its managed desktop services to Windows 7 Enterprise. The main reason for the move is easy to understand. Management felt that Windows 7 was  part of the latest information technology, which will provide increased [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5432:"<p>Rack another one up for Microsoft Windows 7.  TSystems International a subsidiary of Deutsche Telekom AG announced that it is starting the migration operation of  its managed desktop services to Windows 7 Enterprise. The main reason for the move is easy to understand. Management felt that Windows 7 was  part of the latest information technology, which will provide increased security, reduced costs and greater productivity to Deutsche Telekom PC users around the world. This decision is not small it affect 250,000 seats.</p>
<p><a href="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/dtlogo.gif"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-10930" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/dtlogo-400x200.gif" alt="dtlogo 400x200 Deutsche Telekom Moves Computers to Windows 7" width="400" height="200" title="Deutsche Telekom Moves Computers to Windows 7" /></a></p>
<p><strong>Features on the Go</strong></p>
<p>By upgrading to Windows 7, T-Systems is providing greater flexibility and productivity to its external and internal customers at Deutsche Telekom. For example, Windows 7 Enterprise supports roaming profiles that allow employees to easily stay connected with the network while on the go.  It also allows an overall improvement in performance and reboot times. Furthermore, the built-in power management features in Windows 7 will help decrease power consumption, as well as prolong the battery life of laptop computers.</p>
<p><strong>Not Sexy but Productive</strong></p>
<p>Microsoft has long been considered the second player behind Apple&#8217;s innovations. But Microsoft has something going that Apple can&#8217;t reach, and that is grunt work. It is a workhorse. It is not a sexy product but it is productive. Sure, it doesn&#8217;t have the Apps of the iPad2. but in a business environment Microsoft has become the International Business Machine of the modern era.</p>
<p>For many companies, Windows 7 provides them with numerous opportunities to cut costs and reduce workloads. Not only can Windows7 be applied to any hardware appliance, the supporting application software is unique among companies. Do you need a word processor? Go to the Windows Office Suite. Do you need C # development tools? Go to Visual Studio and begin programming. Do you need a multitasking Database? Go to SQL Server 2008. It is there. That is what companies need and are using.</p>
<p>T-Systems is an example of how companies can leverage new features and technologies in order to save time and money and give employees the flexibility they need to stay productive.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>


