</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1300139343;}i:7;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:34:"Internet Explorer 9 Released Today";s:4:"link";s:74:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/14/internet-explorer-9-released-today/";s:8:"comments";s:83:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/14/internet-explorer-9-released-today/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 14 Mar 2011 11:52:34 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:17:"Mike Halsey (MVP)";}s:8:"category";s:41:"Windows 7 NewsHTML5ieIE9internet explorer";s:4:"guid";s:74:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/14/internet-explorer-9-released-today/";s:11:"description";s:345:"Today is the day either the browser wars heat up or they don?t as Microsoft release Internet Explorer 9, their first HTML5 compliant browser and the most standards-compliant web browser they have ever released. Internet Explorer has been haemorrhaging market share ever since the first release of Mozilla Firefox, but in the last couple of [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5185:"<p>Today is the day either the browser wars heat up or they don?t as Microsoft release Internet Explorer 9, their first HTML5 compliant browser and the most standards-compliant web browser they have ever released.</p>
<p>Internet Explorer has been haemorrhaging market share ever since the first release of Mozilla Firefox, but in the last couple of years the browser war has really become a two horse race between Firefox and Google?s Chrome browser.  In this time Internet Explorer has dropped from 95% market share to around 60%.</p>
<p>Microsoft have taken inspiration from their popular competitor Chrome with this release in that the browser window furniture is smaller and less obvious than ever.  Microsoft have said that with many people using Web 2.0 applications in their browser, they didn?t want the browser itself to get in the way of that.</p>
<p>The end result, just like Chrome is a very slimmed-down web browser which is in stark contrast to Firefox which remains the browser of choice for those people who like to use plugins and toolbars.</p>
<p>Internet Explorer does bring very useful new features though, but only for users of Windows 7.  These include the ability to pin websites to the operating system?s taskbar and for the developers of those websites to code jumplists for those icons directly into the site.  Any such site launched form the taskbar takes on the colour properties of the website, making it appear even more that the website is an app, rather than being used in a web browser.</p>
<p>Microsoft have been pushing HTML5 strongly and it?s anticipated that a beta version of their Bing search engine, using HTML5, will also appear in the next week or so.  Google and Mozilla haven?t been so keen to push HTML5 though both claim that their browsers are more HTML5 compliant than IE9.  The reason for this, Microsoft say, is that they are only supporting features in the new web standard that either have or are close to ratification.</p>
<p>It remains to be seen how and if IE9 will help Microsoft regain valuable browser market share.  This will be a long struggle especially as the browser will not run on XP, a move that?s necessary because of OS hardware acceleration that only exists in Vista and Windows 7.  This will not help the company move people off the buggy and insecure Internet Explorer 6 however.</p>


<p>Related posts:<ol><li><a href='http://www.windows7news.com/2010/07/01/internet-explorer-is-gaining-back-usage/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Internet Explorer is Gaining Back Usage'>Internet Explorer is Gaining Back Usage</a></li>
<li><a href='http://www.windows7news.com/2011/01/04/internet-explorer-loses-europe-firefox-king/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Internet Explorer Loses Out In Europe &#8211; Firefox Now King'>Internet Explorer Loses Out In Europe &#8211; Firefox Now King</a></li>
