</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1299948260;}i:12;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:73:"Will the Microsoft/Nokia Alliance Take 2 Years to Start Producing Phones?";s:4:"link";s:94:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/12/microsoftnokia-alliance-2-years-start-producing-phones/";s:8:"comments";s:103:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/12/microsoftnokia-alliance-2-years-start-producing-phones/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 12 Mar 2011 12:13:26 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:17:"Mike Halsey (MVP)";}s:8:"category";s:41:"Windows 7 NewsMicrosoftnokiawindows phone";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://www.windows7news.com/?p=10913";s:11:"description";s:365:"When Microsoft and Nokia announced their strategic partnership the world got terribly excited.  The thought of the world&#8217;s biggest phone manufacturer shipping it&#8217;s new smartphones with the new Windows Phone OS on board is an exciting prospect indeed. Then images leaked of a concept Nokia Windows Phone handset that was sexy indeed just days later [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5908:"<p><a href="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/11x0211nokiaconcept.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-10914" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/11x0211nokiaconcept-150x150.jpg" alt="11x0211nokiaconcept 150x150 Will the Microsoft/Nokia Alliance Take 2 Years to Start Producing Phones?" width="150" height="150" title="Will the Microsoft/Nokia Alliance Take 2 Years to Start Producing Phones?" /></a>When Microsoft and Nokia announced their strategic partnership the world got terribly excited.  The thought of the world&#8217;s biggest phone manufacturer shipping it&#8217;s new smartphones with the new Windows Phone OS on board is an exciting prospect indeed.</p>
<p>Then images leaked of a concept Nokia Windows Phone handset that was sexy indeed just days later and the world got all excited again.  Since then it&#8217;s all gone very quiet.</p>
<p>Now though tech journalist <a href="http://www.zdnet.com/blog/microsoft/nokia-transition-to-windows-phone-to-take-about-two-years/8907?tag=mantle_skin;content" target="_blank">Mary-Jo Foley</a> has uncovered documentation that indicates it could take two years for the Nokia / Microsoft partnership to bear fruit.  In a 200 page document released by the mobile phone giant, she&#8217;s discovered details that the transition to Windows Phone as the company&#8217;s &#8220;primary smartphone platform&#8221; will take &#8220;about two years&#8221;.</p>
<p>This means consumers who are expecting a Nokia Windows phone as early as this summer look set for disappointment.  Indeed this, if true, is very bad news for Windows Phone all round.  At the recent World Mobile Congress exhibition in Barcelona, the world&#8217;s biggest annual mobile phone and smartphone expo, there were new Android handsets aplenty from all the major manufacturers but not a single new Windows Phone.</p>
<p>We all know that Windows Phone hasn&#8217;t, so far, met sales expectations but now questions are being asked if Microsoft&#8217;s own partners are beginning to go cold on the OS.  This means that Microsoft need Nokia probably far more than Nokia need Windows Phone.  A two year wait for a handset could be the first nail in Windows Phone&#8217;s coffin.</p>
<p>The reason for the two year transition is apparently to &#8220;retain and transition the installed base of approximately 200 million Symbian owners to Nokia Windows Phone smartphones over time&#8221;.  It&#8217;s not good news for Windows Phone or Nokia fans, of which there are a great many millions.</p>
<p>We&#8217;ll have to wait and see what happens in the long term, but in the mean time Windows Phone needs some new handsets to be announced from companies such as HTC, Samsung and LG.  There hasn&#8217;t been a single new handset announced since the Windows Phone launch last October and as the smartphone market pushes ahead with sometimes alarming speed, this slowdown is something many industry watchers will be keeping a <em>very</em> close eye on.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>


