</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1299577743;}i:17;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:17:"A PC and a Tablet";s:4:"link";s:49:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/07/pc-tablet/";s:8:"comments";s:58:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/07/pc-tablet/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 08 Mar 2011 04:35:00 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:6:"GGarza";}s:8:"category";s:26:"Windows 7 Newsipadpctablet";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://www.windows7news.com/?p=10900";s:11:"description";s:330:"A PC is a well defined device. You know, monitor, motherboard, CPU, memory, mouse, keyboard, and software. And a tablet, is that a PC? Last year the answer was clear from Microsoft Until now, Microsoft officials have claimed that iPads are not PCs. And this position is easy to understand. If iPads are counted as PCs, Apple [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5134:"<p>A PC is a well defined device. You know, monitor, motherboard, CPU, memory, mouse, keyboard, and software. And a tablet, is that a PC? Last year the answer was clear from Microsoft Until now, Microsoft officials have claimed that iPads are not PCs. And this position is easy to understand. If iPads are counted as PCs, Apple would be the No. 2 PC vendor.  And who wants that?</p>
<p>So here is the question are the slates/tablets running Windows 7 PCs?  Microsoft is straddling the fence. A PC is not a tablet but a tablet is a PC.  Their campaign isn?t new. In fact,  Microsoft officials pointed to it  some time after the Consumer Electronics Show in January. But it does make plain the Softies? dilemma in the tablet/slate space. Last year, Microsoft tried to<a href="http://www.zdnet.com/blog/microsoft/at-microsoft-theres-a-thin-line-between-a-tablet-and-a-slate/6412"> </a>undo the  confusion it created over the company?s tablet vs. slate vs. PC rhetoric. To differentiate between tablets and slates running Windows 7 vs. tablets and slates running Windows Embedded Compact 7, Microsoft  ended up saying something to the effect that Windows Embedded Compact slates were for content consumption, but get this,  Windows-based ones were for both consumption and creation. No Really!</p>
<p><a href="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/apple-ipad-camera.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-10901" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/apple-ipad-camera-400x294.jpg" alt="apple ipad camera 400x294 A PC and a Tablet" width="400" height="294" title="A PC and a Tablet" /></a></p>
<p><strong>What is Apple&#8217;s Take on This?</strong></p>
<p>Well we know what Apple did last week. It drove home the idea of what the tablet/PC argument is about.  The iPad and iPad 2 can do both content consumption and creation. This doesn?t mean PCs are at the end of the line or that we are now in a post-PC era.  To be in the post PC world we would not have PC&#8217;s or Mac&#8217;s to contend with. Still the PC has been redefined. If you are a gamer, a business, or entrepreneur, then you can use a PC. But the ordinary consumer will look at the PC in a different way. Mainly due to the invention of Apps, small programs that do one thing. They could have been devised for PC&#8217;s but the small size of the tablet changed everything.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>


