<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:D7DqB2pKExk"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:D7DqB2pKExk" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:I9og5sOYxJI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=I9og5sOYxJI" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=6AXudYYHSMc:6FYrkIwvRlg:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a>
</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1299346625;}i:22;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:43:"Empty Your Trash with minibin for Windows 7";s:4:"link";s:69:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/05/empty-trash-minibin-windows-7/";s:8:"comments";s:78:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/05/empty-trash-minibin-windows-7/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 05 Mar 2011 05:35:43 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:5:"Jason";}s:8:"category";s:58:"Windows 7 Newse-sushiminibinrecycle bintoolstrashWindows 7";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://www.windows7news.com/?p=10881";s:11:"description";s:134:"e-sushi's minibin sets out to take that clean look and make it even more useful by combining your recycle bin with a system tray icon.";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:6176:"<p>One of the many complaints that users had about previous versions of Windows was that the system tray and notifications from that area were overly ugly and intrusive. If you had a lot of third-party software installed on Windows, you no doubt had a system tray full of icons that you may not have had a clue as to what they actually did. This is just one of the issues Microsoft set out to change in Windows 7.</p>
<p>Windows 7 now sports a much cleaner-looking system tray and  e-sushi&#8217;s <em>minibin</em> sets out to take that clean look and make it even more useful by combining your recycle bin with a system tray icon, further clearing your desktop of non-essential icons.</p>
<p><em>minibin</em> will sit in  your system tray with a spartan-looking icon and serve almost as much purpose as the recycle bin desktop icon. The only drawback I can see with <em>minibin</em> is the inability to drag files onto the icon to recycle. However, you can still right-click and choose to delete your items or even double-click the icon to empty the trash.</p>
<p>Even when the bin is full, <em>minibin</em> keeps that same minimalist look of the recycle bin.</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-10882" href="http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/05/empty-trash-minibin-windows-7/minibin3/"><img class="size-full wp-image-10882 aligncenter" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/minibin3.jpg" alt="minibin3 Empty Your Trash with minibin for Windows 7" width="217" height="68" title="Empty Your Trash with minibin for Windows 7" /></a></p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-10883" href="http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/05/empty-trash-minibin-windows-7/minibin2/"><img class="size-full wp-image-10883 aligncenter" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/minibin2.jpg" alt="minibin2 Empty Your Trash with minibin for Windows 7" width="233" height="65" title="Empty Your Trash with minibin for Windows 7" /></a></p>
<p>You have the ability to configure certain options in <em>minibin</em>.</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-10884" href="http://www.windows7news.com/2011/03/05/empty-trash-minibin-windows-7/minibin1/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-10884 aligncenter" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/minibin1-400x369.jpg" alt="minibin1 400x369 Empty Your Trash with minibin for Windows 7" width="400" height="369" title="Empty Your Trash with minibin for Windows 7" /></a></p>
<p>I typically keep one icon on my desktop to avoid clutter and until now that has been the recycle bin, but with <em>minibin</em>, I have been able to keep the functionality of the recycle bin and keep it visible at all times, while at the same time losing the extra icon.</p>
<p>I&#8217;d like to give credit for this cool little piece of free software to the most recent Windows Weekly podcast starring Paul Thurrott and Leo Laporte. Let me know in the comments below if you find this little piece of software helpful or if you&#8217;ve found another solution to keeping your Recycle Bin off the desktop.</p>
<p>Head on over to<a href="http://www.e-sushi.net/" target="_blank"> e-sushi&#8217;s website </a>if you&#8217;d like to give <em>minibin</em> a spin.</p>


