</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1298781493;}i:35;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:38:"Microsoft?s Vision of Future Computing";s:4:"link";s:74:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/26/microsofts-vision-future-computing/";s:8:"comments";s:83:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/26/microsofts-vision-future-computing/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 26 Feb 2011 22:20:55 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:5:"Jason";}s:8:"category";s:86:"Windows 7 NewsKinectMicrosoftmicrosoft researchnatural-user interfacesurfacetech forum";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://www.windows7news.com/?p=10831";s:11:"description";s:135:"At Tech Forum, Microsoft Research showed off some of the things they've been and currently are working on in terms of future computing.";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5008:"<p>Between Windows 95 and Windows 7, Microsoft took a lot of somewhat-deserved flak for not being innovative for many years while they sat on their enormous market share lead. As companies like Google and Apple rose even more into prominence in computing and even leading in the mobile space, many of us wondered what Microsoft was doing and when they would figure out that they were slowly fading in consumers minds as the leading computing company in the world.</p>
<p>Apple really polished the touch interface with the iPhone, so much so, that it took a few years for other companies to match the quality of touch-gesture user interfaces and some companies and mobile manufacturers still aren&#8217;t quite there yet. We are finally at the point where many companies seem to have touch-based UI&#8217;s down, but what&#8217;s next?</p>
<p>If you ask Microsoft, the natural user interface is the next step. Found in addition to the Xbox 360, the Kinect is seemingly where Microsoft is hedging their bets. Microsoft is also expanding their touch-based computing to things like the new Microsoft Surface they unveiled back at CES 2011.</p>
<p>At Microsoft&#8217;s<em> Tech Forum</em>, Microsoft Research showed off some of the things they&#8217;ve been and currently are working on in terms of future computing. Below is 4-minute video directed by Greg Mundie, Chief Research and Strategy Officer at Microsoft. The video broadly lays out how Microsoft see&#8217;s the future of computing and is interesting to note that some of the ideas glossed over have been rumored for the next version of Windows.</p>
<p><a href="http://microsoft-news.com/microsoft-ready-to-blow-your-mind-with-future-computers/" target="_blank">Take a look at the Microsoft Tech Forum video here.</a></p>
<p><a href="http://microsoft-news.com/microsoft-demos-interesting-tablet-ui-concept/" target="_blank">Here is an interesting and unrelated tablet UI concept using Windows 7.</a></p>
<p>It looks as if Microsoft is readying themselves for the future of computing with Kinect. Do you guys think the natural-interface experience that Microsoft seems to be betting on is truly the future of computing?</p>
<p>Source: <a href="http://microsoft-news.com/microsoft-ready-to-blow-your-mind-with-future-computers/" target="_blank">Microsoft News</a></p>


