<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:D7DqB2pKExk"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:D7DqB2pKExk" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:I9og5sOYxJI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=I9og5sOYxJI" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=Kdai4BBB6sI:HZXEWDw_mcs:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a>
</div>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:64:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/25/coming-slate-tablet/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"35";}s:7:"summary";s:283:"A new Windows 7 slate tablet is in the works and should be starting in April 2011.  Microsoft is looking for a way to rock in the  Apple?s iPad and Android market with it&#8217;s own product so it is hoping that the new slate will do the trick. So what is the product? It comes [...]";s:12:"atom_content";s:5565:"<p>A new Windows 7 slate tablet is in the works and should be starting in April 2011.  Microsoft is looking for a way to rock in the  Apple?s iPad and Android market with it&#8217;s own product so it is hoping that the new slate will do the trick.</p>
<p><strong>So what is the product?</strong></p>
<p>It comes from Fujitsu which has launched a secure Slate PC for Business Class. The coming slate, runs <a href="http://windows7news.com/windows-7-professional/">Windows 7 Professional</a>. It supports pen-based input, and  touch; it also offers an optional smartcard reader for extra security. In fact, the Slate meets the stringent ICT security requirements of  governments and businesses. It is developed to  meet enterprise mobile computing demands and integrate into  existing ICT infrastructures.</p>
<p><a href="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/Fugitsu-Slate.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-10829" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/Fugitsu-Slate-400x300.jpg" alt="Fugitsu Slate 400x300 The Coming Fujitsu Windows 7 Slate Tablet" width="400" height="300" title="The Coming Fujitsu Windows 7 Slate Tablet" /></a></p>
<p><strong>A Different Outlook</strong></p>
<p>Most enterprises struggle to keep mobile devices out of their networks because of the security breaches that can come. But Fujitsu proposes  an alternative approach with the introduction of a secondary companion device  designed for maximum interoperability with business environments.  In fact, integration is provided by using Microsoft&#8217;s Windows  7 operating system. You can contain costs when you use the same software already deployed in the business enterprise. This allows you to avoid  additional licensing and rollout costs.</p>
<p><strong>Hardware Specs</strong></p>
<p>The STYLISTIC Q550 has a full work day  battery runtime of 10 hours and an  anti-glare 10.1-inch screen that allows  for use both indoors and outdoors. Network or wireless connectivity comes through  the inclusion of WLAN, Bluetooth and optional mobile broadband 3G/UMTS.</p>
<p><strong>Touch and Go</strong></p>
<p>Mobile data entry is easier because it combines a multiple touch  interface with precise and pressure-sensitive pen input. It also automatically recognizes when users are working with a pen,  this allows users to rest their hand on the screen when writing. The handwriting recognition software converts input to text, and when the pen is  not in use, the slate PC automatically readjusts to a touch interface.</p>
<p>Source: <a href="http://www.fujitsu.com/global/news/pr/archives/month/2011/20110224-01.html">Fugitsu</a></p>
