</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1298662121;}i:37;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:44:"Bad News?10% of Windows Phone 7 Updates Fail";s:4:"link";s:79:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/24/bad-news10-windows-phone-7-updates-fail/";s:8:"comments";s:88:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/24/bad-news10-windows-phone-7-updates-fail/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 24 Feb 2011 22:52:46 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:6:"GGarza";}s:8:"category";s:14:"Windows 7 News";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://www.windows7news.com/?p=10824";s:11:"description";s:318:"Things didn?t go too well for the first Windows Phone 7 Update. Not when as many as 10% of installations failing to install correctly. So why did it Fail? There are two reasons. Of the 10 percent of users who did experience a problem, nearly half failed because a bad Internet connection or insufficient computer [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5465:"<p>Things didn?t go too well for the first Windows Phone 7 Update. Not when as many as 10% of installations failing to install correctly.</p>
<p><a href="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/microsoft-windows-phone-7.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-10827" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/microsoft-windows-phone-7.jpg" alt="microsoft windows phone 7 Bad News...10% of Windows Phone 7 Updates Fail" width="400" height="400" title="Bad News...10% of Windows Phone 7 Updates Fail" /></a></p>
<p><strong>So why did it Fail?</strong></p>
<p>There are two reasons. Of the 10 percent of users who did experience a problem, nearly half failed because a bad Internet connection or insufficient computer storage space.</p>
<p>Hmm.</p>
<p>10% - Now that?s a big number. In fact, without stretching, you can consider this a shocking failure. Not only that, it?s very bad for the Microsoft brand that 10% of WP7 early adopters have seen errors on the very first update. Just think of what some users are saying??I bought a Microsoft Windows Phone 7, and now I wish I had bought an iPhone.? That can?t be good.</p>
<p>So there are bad Internet connections that caused one problem and a lack free space on the computer caused the other. Let?s look at it from a different perspective. Since Zune software is used with the Windows Phone 7,</p>
<p>Why doesn?t Microsoft?s Zune software inform users that there?s insufficient disk space before attempting the install?</p>
<p>Secondly, how much free disk space does a WP7 update really need if it affects so many people by it? provide a download manager to deal with any problems caused by a bad Internet connection?</p>
<p>If these concerns are real, then why didn?t they prevent the failure?</p>
<p>But this update proves that when it comes to handling critical updates the Zune software is fragile and limited. Moreover, it means that it is necessary to improve the software significantly before Microsoft starts pushing more updates down to users.</p>
<p>And the other half, bad network connections, what about that? Were they bricked Samsungs? It is not clear yet. But in either case, Microsoft should have done a better job handling the downloads.</p>
<p>Source: <a href="http://www.zdnet.com/blog/hardware/10-percent-of-windows-phone-7-update-installations-failed/11605?tag=mantle_skin;content">Zdnet</a></p>
