<li><a href='http://www.windows7news.com/2010/12/15/windows-phone-mango-update-big/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Windows Phone &#8216;Mango&#8217; Update Said To Be A Big One'>Windows Phone &#8216;Mango&#8217; Update Said To Be A Big One</a></li>
</ol></p><div class="feedflare">
<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:D7DqB2pKExk"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:D7DqB2pKExk" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:I9og5sOYxJI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=I9og5sOYxJI" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=ur4-4P8n61k:A1fEtgs3TL8:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a>
</div>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:78:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/23/truth-windows-phone-update-issues/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"88";}s:7:"summary";s:184:"If you've been reading the news headlines surrounding Windows Phone's recent update, then you've probably heard all about the doom and gloom that supposedly surrounds the small update.";s:12:"atom_content";s:5511:"<p>If you&#8217;ve been reading the news headlines surrounding Windows Phone&#8217;s recent update, then you&#8217;ve probably heard all about the doom and gloom that supposedly surrounds the small update. While it&#8217;s true that some users are experiencing issues with the new update, the story from Microsoft is that the large majority of Windows Phone users are updating without an issue and most of the users with problems are a direct result of poor internet connectivity or a lack of space with which to install the update.</p>
<p>Here is what the official word from Microsoft is taken directly from their Windows Phone Blog:</p>
<blockquote><p>Contrary to some of the gloomy headlines out there, our preliminary internal data paints a very different picture about update progress:</p>
<ul>
<li>90 percent of people who?ve received an update notification have installed the new software patch successfully. (So when your turn to download it arrives, chances are good this will be a non-event.)</li>
<li>Of the 10 percent who did experience a problem, nearly half failed for two basic reasons?a bad Internet connection or insufficient computer storage space. Luckily, both are easy to fix.</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>
<p>For the small percentage of you who have had an issue and are frustrated, Microsoft feels your pain:</p>
<blockquote><p>Has the update process has gone perfectly? No?but few large-scale software updates ever do, and the engineering team here was prepared. Of course, when it?s your phone that?s having a problem?or you?re the one waiting?it?s still aggravating. That?s why we?re committed to learning from our first update and improving the process. We know we have work to do, and we won?t be satisfied until you are.</p>
<p>As the teams here continue to monitor the ongoing update, I?ll report back if there are any other noteworthy developments. Meanwhile, let me address a few other questions I?ve been seeing, here and elsewhere.</p></blockquote>
<p>They&#8217;ve also, finally, taken the time to do<a href="http://windowsteamblog.com/windows_phone/b/windowsphone/archive/2011/02/23/more-answers-about-our-first-software-update.aspx" target="_blank"> a little Q&amp;A</a> on their Windows Phone blog which posts and answers some of the most frequently asked questions about the update process, so if you are a Windows Phone user, you may want to head on over and check out their answers before attempting the update yourself. This may help to quell any possible user-created problems you might have run into.</p>
<p>As for my Windows Phone (Samsung Focus), I&#8217;m still waiting to receive the update which may or may not have been pulled by Microsoft.</p>


