</div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1298396419;}i:42;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:44:"Microsoft Announces Kinect SDK for Windows 7";s:4:"link";s:80:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/22/microsoft-announces-kinect-sdk-windows-7/";s:8:"comments";s:89:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/22/microsoft-announces-kinect-sdk-windows-7/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 22 Feb 2011 10:55:37 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Robert Boland";}s:8:"category";s:112:"Windows 7 HardwareWindows 7 NewsKinectkinect controlling windows 7kinect hackkinect sdkMicrosoftwindowsWindows 7";s:4:"guid";s:36:"http://www.windows7news.com/?p=10811";s:11:"description";s:319:"Microsoft have finally announced that they will be releasing an official SDK (software development kit) for Kinect this Spring. Up until now, all we&#8217;ve had is some hackers doing there very best to crack the device to make it perform some simple actions. They did manage to mess around with it a bit, much to [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5529:"<p>Microsoft have finally announced that they will be releasing an official SDK (software development kit) for Kinect this Spring. Up until now, all we&#8217;ve had is some hackers doing there very best to crack the device to make it perform some simple actions. They did manage to mess around with it a bit, much to Microsoft&#8217;s dismay, but they appear to have warmed to the idea somewhat. At CES Steve Ballmer did briefly mention that Microsoft would officially support Kinect integration with Windows, but he was very vague about the date.</p>
<p>Now it&#8217;s official, as posted on the Microsoft <a href="http://blogs.technet.com/b/microsoft_blog/archive/2011/02/21/kinect-for-windows-sdk-to-arrive-spring-2011.aspx" target="_blank">Technet blog</a>. Microsoft are saying that the Kinect for Windows SDK will allow all third-party developers to create software titles that make use of Kinect motion sensor that can be plugged directly into a Windows PC. And this time they won&#8217;t have to hack it. This fist edition is a noncommercial &#8220;starter version&#8221; SDK that will give users access to a wide range of Kinect system information such as audio, system application-programming interfaces, and direct control of the Kinect sensor.</p>
<p><a href="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/kinectwin7sdk.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-10812" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/kinectwin7sdk-600x281.jpg" alt="kinectwin7sdk 600x281 Microsoft Announces Kinect SDK for Windows 7" width="600" height="281" title="Microsoft Announces Kinect SDK for Windows 7" /></a></p>
<p>The only thing is you will not be able to charge for any software developed with it. However they do plan on releasing a full commercial version of the SDK sometime later this year, which will allow developers to charge for the software they develop.</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;Microsoft&#8217;s investments in natural user interfaces are vital to our long-term vision of creating computers that are intuitive to use and able to do far more for us,&#8221; The fruits of these research investments are manifesting across many of our products, Kinect for Xbox 360 among them&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>It certainly will be interesting to see what developers can come up with now to make full use of Kinect. Undoubtedly the official Microsoft SDK will give them an even wider array of opportunities than the current method of hacking it. To date they&#8217;ve managed to use Kinect to turn the sensor bar into a 3D camera, allow for multitouch photo manipulation without the need for a touch screen, and make it possible to create midair 3D doodles.</p>
<p>What would you like to see Kinect used for with Windows?</p>
<p>Let us know in the comments below</p>


