<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:D7DqB2pKExk"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:D7DqB2pKExk" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:gIN9vFwOqvQ" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:I9og5sOYxJI"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=I9og5sOYxJI" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?i=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?a=W3SHuxJMMRM:741ZyKVF9iA:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/MicrosoftWindows7News?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a>
</div>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:77:"http://www.windows7news.com/2011/02/21/windows-phone-update-rolls-today/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"11";}s:7:"summary";s:328:"Microsoft have announced that the first Windows Phone update is rolling out to users today.  In a post on the Windows Phone blog, they said &#8220;Starting today, some of you might see something new on your Windows Phone: A message announcing that a software update is available. Woo hoo!&#8221; They go on to explain that [...]";s:12:"atom_content";s:6618:"<p><a href="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/WindowsPhoneLogoOrangeThumb3.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-10803" src="http://wincom.eurekaconsultinglimited.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/WindowsPhoneLogoOrangeThumb3.jpg" alt="WindowsPhoneLogoOrangeThumb3 First Windows Phone Update Rolls Out Today" width="150" height="150" title="First Windows Phone Update Rolls Out Today" /></a>Microsoft have announced that the first Windows Phone update is rolling out to users today.  In a post on the Windows Phone <a href="http://windowsteamblog.com/windows_phone/b/windowsphone/archive/2011/02/21/our-first-windows-phone-update-and-how-to-get-it.aspx" target="_blank">blog</a>, they said &#8220;Starting today, some of you might see something new on your Windows Phone: A message announcing that a software update is available. <em>Woo hoo</em>!&#8221;</p>
<p>They go on to explain that this <em>isn&#8217;t</em> the update containing the cut and paste functionality that we&#8217;ve been expecting.  So what is in it?</p>
<blockquote><p>This first update for Windows Phone is designed to improve the software update process itself. So while it might not sound exciting, it?s still important because it?s paving the way for all future goodie-filled updates to your phone, such as copy and paste or improved Marketplace search.</p></blockquote>
<p>So the update is intended to provide patches and performance improvements.  The lack of the cut and paste functionality though means that the company is deviating from the expected update timetable.</p>
<p>The update will begin to roll out to users today though Microsoft say &#8220;to help ensure the process goes smoothly, it won?t be sent to everyone at once. So you might see an update message before your spouse, co-worker, or neighbor (or vice versa).&#8221; which is a sensible way to make sure their servers don&#8217;t fall over.  It&#8217;s the way Windows updates and especially service packs have been rolled out for years and it&#8217;s common practice in the tech industry.</p>
<p>So how can you get the update?  Microsoft say.</p>
<blockquote><p>You?ll need to connect your phone to your computer and update it using either the <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/windowsphone/en-us/apps/zune-software.aspx">Zune software for your PC</a> or the <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/windowsphone/en-us/apps/mac-connector.aspx">Windows Phone 7 Connector for Mac</a> (depending on which kind of computer you have).</p>
<p>So just install one of these programs, connect your phone to your computer via the USB cable, and then follow the on-screen instructions. I also strongly encourage you to check out our <a href="http://www.microsoft.com/windowsphone/en-us/howto/wp7/basics/how-do-i-update-my-phone-software.aspx">step-by-step guide for updating your phone</a> on the Windows Phone website.</p>
<p>One last important word: If you?ve installed the Zune software or the Windows Phone 7 Connector in the past, you might actually need to update that program first <em>and then</em> use it to update your phone. If that?s the case, you?ll know. Just follow the on-screen instructions, <em>restart the software</em>, and then connect your phone.</p></blockquote>
<p>There is no word on when the next update containign cut and paste and perhaps other features will roll out as yet though they are describing this update as &#8220;the first of many&#8221;.  Does this mean that Microsoft are finally listening to consumers who want small and regular updates?  We&#8217;ll have to wait and see on that one.  You can read the full blog post <a href="http://windowsteamblog.com/windows_phone/b/windowsphone/archive/2011/02/21/our-first-windows-phone-update-and-how-to-get-it.aspx" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>


